<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec19-MatrixLinearTransformation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Matrix of a Linear Transformations</title>

  <p>
    <alert>UNDER CONSTRUCTION...</alert>
  </p>

  <p>
    Notice that any vector in <m>\R^2</m> can be written as a linear combination of <m>\v{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{e}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
  </p>

  <proof>
    <title>Quick proof of this claim</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m> be an arbitrary vector in <m>\R^2</m>. 
      Then
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = x\v{e}_1 + y\v{e}_2
      </md>
      Proved! 
    </p>
  </proof>

  <p>
    <m>\left\{ \v{e}_1, \v{e}_2 \right\}</m> is called the <term>standard basis</term> of <m>\R^2</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    For <m>\R^n</m>, the standard basis consists of the vectors <m>\left\{\v{e}_1, \v{e}_2, \ldots, \v{e}_n\right\}</m> where the <m>k</m>-th entry of <m>\v{e}_k</m> is a <m>1</m> and all of the rest are zeros. 
    Clearly these are all <m>n</m>-dimensional vectors. 
    That means the <m>\v{e}_1</m> is actually a different vector depending on which <m>\R^n</m> you are working with. 
  </p>

  <p>
    For example, <m>\v{e}_1</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, but <m>\v{e}_1</m> in <m>\R^3</m> is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
    They are NOT the same vectors! 
  </p>

  <p>
    Combining this fact with the two properties that every linear transformation satisfies, we can see that every linear combination defined on <m>\R^2</m> (this works for <m>\R^n</m> as well, but let's start small!) is actually determined by what it does to the standard basis vectors <m>\v{e}_1</m> and <m>\v{e}_2</m>. 
  </p>

  <proof>
    <title>Quick proof of this claim</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>\v{x}</m> be a vector in <m>\R^2</m>. 
      Then there exist scalars <m>a, b \in \R</m> such that
      <md>
        \v{x} = a\v{e}_1 + b\v{e}_2
      </md>
      Then for any linear transformation <m>T</m> defined on <m>\R^2</m>, we have
      <md>
        T(\v{x}) = T(a\v{e}_1 + b\v{e}_2) = aT(\v{e}_1) + bT(\v{e}_2)
      </md>
      So the output of <m>T</m> at <m>\v{x}</m> is completely determined by the output of <m>T</m> at <m>\v{e}_1</m> and <m>\v{e}_2</m>.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <p>
    We can use this fact to figure out how to find the matrix for a linear transformation (and in doing so, we really prove that such a matrix will always exist for any linear transformation)!
  </p>

  <example>
    <p>
      Suppose that <m>T: \R^2 \to \R^3</m> is a linear transformation such that
      <md>
        T\lp \v{e}_1 \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
        \qquad \text{ and } \qquad
        T\lp \v{e}_2 \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      What is the matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m> for all <m>\v{x} \in \R^2</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider any vector <m>\v{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m> in <m>\R^2</m>.
      We know that
      <md>
        <mrow> T\lp \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \rp \amp= T\lp x\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= xT\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp + yT\lp \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= x\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + y\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 2x + y \\ 2y \\ 3x + 3y \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
      </md>
      Notice that the output is what we would get if we multiplied the matrix <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> by the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m>! 
      So
      <md>
        T\lp \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      We found the matrix that goes with this linear transformation!
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    Notice that in the above example, <alert>the columns of our matrix were the outputs of the standard basis vectors</alert>. 
    That tells us exactly how to find a matrix for any linear transformation!
  </p>

  <p>
    Suppose <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> is a linear transformation. 
    To find the matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T</m> is given by the rule <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>, we...
    <ol marker="Step 1:">
      <li>
        <p>
          Figure out <m>T\lp \v{e_1} \rp, T\lp \v{e_2} \rp, \ldots T\lp \v{e_n} \rp</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Write the matrix that has columns <m>T\lp \v{e_1} \rp, T\lp \v{e_2} \rp, \ldots T\lp \v{e_n} \rp</m>: 
          <md>
            A = \begin{bmatrix} T\lp \v{e_1} \rp \amp T\lp \v{e_2} \rp \amp \cdots \amp T\lp \v{e_n} \rp \end{bmatrix}
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Pat yourself on the back
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    Special terminology! 
    This matrix <m>A</m> that we found is called the <term>standard matrix</term> for the linear transformation <m>T</m>. 
  </p>

  <example>
    <p>
      Let <m>T: \R^2 \to \R^2</m> be a linear transformation given by
      <md>
        T\lp \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 2x + 3y \\ 5x + 7y \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Let's find the matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m> for all <m>\v{x} \in \R^2</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Step 1: In this case, <m>\v{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{e}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
      So
      <md>
        T(\v{e}_1) = T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}
        \qquad \text{ and } \qquad
        T(\v{e}_2) = T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Step 2: <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} T(\v{e}_1)\amp T(\v{e}_2) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's check to see if <m>A</m> really works!
      <md>
        A\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2x + 3y \\ 5x + 7y \end{bmatrix} 
      </md>
      Woo! 
    </p>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Find the matrix that corresponds to the linear transformation <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^2</m> given by
      <md>
        T\lp \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} x + 3y + 7z \\ 3x + 5y - 8z \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
    </p>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Step 1: In this case, since the domain is <m>\R^3</m>, our standard basis vectors are <m>\v{e}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, <m>\v{e}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>\v{e}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
        Evaluating the transformation at each gives:
        <md>
          T(\v{e}_1) = T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix},
        </md>
        <md>
          T(\v{e}_2) = T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix},
        </md>
        <md>
          T(\v{e}_3) = T\lp \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -8 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Step 2: We form the matrix by placing these resulting vectors into the columns.
        <md>
          A = \begin{bmatrix} T(\v{e}_1)\amp T(\v{e}_2)\amp T(\v{e}_3) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp 7 \\ 3 \amp 5 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Let's check to see if <m>A</m> really works!
        <md>
          A\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp 7 \\ 3 \amp 5 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x + 3y + 7z \\ 3x + 5y - 8z \end{bmatrix} 
        </md>
        Yay! 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    It turns out that rotations and reflections are also linear transformations! 
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Let's find a matrix for a rotation <m>\theta</m> in <m>\R^2</m>!</alert>
    We need to figure out what such a rotation does to the vectors <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Let's suppose that the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m> is the result of rotating <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> counterclockwise by the angle <m>\theta</m>. 
    This vector can be represented as an arrow starting at the origin and ending at the point <m>(x, y)</m>. 
    We can draw a triangle to figure out the exact coordinates of the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
  </p>

  <image source="sec18-RotationalMatrix-UnitCircle.png" width="50%"></image>

  <p>
    The <m>x</m>-coordinate will be <m>\cos(\theta)</m> and the <m>y</m>-coordinate will be <m>\sin(\theta)</m>. 
    So the rotation takes <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> to <m>\begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    If we also draw the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and rotate it (counterclockwise) by an angle of <m>\theta</m>, we get a picture like this: 
  </p>

  <image source="sec18-RotationalMatrix-RotatingTriangle.png" width="50%"></image>

  <p>
    This time, the <m>x</m>-coordinate will be <m>-\sin(\theta)</m> and the <m>y</m>-coordinate will be <m>\cos(\theta)</m>. 
    So the rotation takes <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> to <m>\begin{bmatrix} -\sin(\theta) \\ \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <em>Note:</em> These pictures make it easy to see this is true when <m>\theta</m> is between <m>0^\circ</m> and <m>90^\circ</m>, 
    To see that this is true regardless of how big <m>\theta</m> is, you can either look at cases in all of the four quadrants or you can use trig identities. 
  </p>

  <p>
    This means that you can find any rotation matrix by plugging <m>\theta</m> into
    <md>
      R_\theta = \begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \amp -\sin(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \amp \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix}
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Now let's find a matrix for the reflection across the line <m>y = mx</m>!</alert>
    We need fo figure out what happens to <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> when we reflect them across the line <m>y = mx</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    From analytic geometry, we know that the slope of any line perpendicular to <m>y = mx</m> will have slope <m>-\frac{1}{m}</m>. 
    We want to find the line through <m>(1,0)</m> that has slope <m>-\frac{1}{m}</m>. 
    That is because we need to find the intersection of that line with <m>y = mx</m> to get the midpoint of the segment between <m>(1,0)</m> and the point we get after reflecting <m>(1,0)</m>. 
  </p>

  <image source="sec18-ReflectionalMatrix.png" width="50%"></image>
  
  <p>
    That perpendicular line is given by <m>y - 0 = -\frac{1}{m}(x - 1)</m>, which simplifies to <m>y = -\frac{1}{m}x + \frac{1}{m}</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Now let's find the point of intersection! 
    Substituting <m>y = mx</m> into this equation, we get 
    <md>
      mx = -\frac{1}{m}x + \frac{1}{m}
      \qquad \implies \qquad 
      m^2x = -x + 1
    </md>
    This means that <m>x = \frac{1}{1 + m^2}</m>. 
    Then substituting again, we get <m>y = m\frac{1}{1 + m^2}</m>.
    So the midpoint between <m>(1,0)</m> and the result of reflecting <m>(1,0)</m> across the line <m>y = mx</m> is <m>\lp \frac{1}{1 + m^2}, m\frac{1}{1 + m^2} \rp</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    The midpoint formula tells us that the midpoint of a segment between points <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m> is <m>\lp \frac{x_1 + x_2}{2}, \frac{y_1 + y_2}{2} \rp</m>.
    So 
    <md>
      \lp \frac{1}{1 + m^2}, m\frac{1}{1 + m^2} \rp = \lp \frac{1 + x}{2}, \frac{0 + y}{2} \rp
    </md>
    where <m>(x,y)</m> is the point we are looking for. 
    This gives us the equations
    <md>
      \begin{cases}
        \frac{1}{1 + m^2} = \frac{1 + x}{2} \\
        m\frac{1}{1 + m^2} = \frac{y}{2}
      \end{cases}
    </md>
    Solving these equations, we get 
    <md>
      \begin{cases}
        x = \frac{1 - m^2}{1 + m^2} \\
        y = \frac{2m}{1 + m^2}
      \end{cases}  
    </md>
    So the reflection takes <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>\lp \frac{1 - m^2}{1 + m^2}, \frac{2m}{1 + m^2} \rp</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    A similar method can be used to find out that the reflection takes the point <m>(0,1)</m> to the point <m>\lp \frac{2m}{1 + m^2}, \frac{m^2 - 1}{1 + m^2} \rp</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Converting these to column vectors, the matrix for reflecting across the line <m>y = mx</m> is given by
    <md>
      R_m = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1 - m^2}{1 + m^2} \amp \frac{2m}{1 + m^2} \\ \frac{2m}{1 + m^2} \amp \frac{m^2 - 1}{1 + m^2} \end{bmatrix}
    </md>
    Pulling out the common factor, we can rewrite this as
    <md>
      R_m = \frac{1}{1 + m^2} \begin{bmatrix} 1 - m^2 \amp 2m \\ 2m \amp m^2 - 1 \end{bmatrix}
    </md>
  </p>

  <exercise>
    <p>
      Now let's help out Richard with his research! 
      (yes, this is actually something Richard worked on in a research project before, but minus the part with heavy abstract algebra theory part)
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose we want to construct a regular hexagon centered at the origin. 
      What are the coordinates of the vertices? 
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's start by pinning down one of the six vertices at <m>(1,0)</m>. 
      Then what are the other five coordinates for this regular hexagon? 
    </p>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Another fantastic way to find these coordinates is by using a linear transformation! Since the hexagon is regular, each vertex is a <m>60^\circ</m> counterclockwise rotation from the previous one around the origin.
      </p>

      <p>
        The standard matrix for a rotation by an angle <m>\theta</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is:
        <md>
          R_\theta = \begin{bmatrix} \cos \theta \amp -\sin \theta \\ \sin \theta \amp \cos \theta \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        For <m>\theta = 60^\circ</m>, our rotation matrix becomes:
        <md>
          R_{60^\circ} = \begin{bmatrix} \cos 60^\circ \amp -\sin 60^\circ \\ \sin 60^\circ \amp \cos 60^\circ \end{bmatrix} 
          = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        We start with our pinned vertex as a column vector, <m>\v{v}_0 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. To find each subsequent vertex, we multiply the previous vector by <m>R_{60^\circ}</m>:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\v{v}_1 = R_{60^\circ}\v{v}_0 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\v{v}_2 = R_{60^\circ}\v{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{4} - \frac{3}{4} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\v{v}_3 = R_{60^\circ}\v{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{4} - \frac{3}{4} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\v{v}_4 = R_{60^\circ}\v{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\v{v}_5 = R_{60^\circ}\v{v}_4 = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\frac{1}{4} + \frac{3}{4} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Translating these column vectors back into coordinate points yields the same five remaining vertices!
      </p>
    </solution>
      
  </exercise>

  <p>
    There are some special linear transformations, and we will focus on <alert>surjection</alert> and <alert>injection</alert>: 
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-SurjectiveTransformation">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A mapping <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> is a <alert>surjection</alert> (or <alert>onto</alert> <m>\R^m</m>) if each <m>\v{b}\in \R^m</m> is the image of at least one <m>\v{x} \in \R^n</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        That is, <em>every</em> element in the codomain of <m>T</m> is an image of the mapping. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="def-InjectiveTransformation">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A mapping <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> is an <alert>injection</alert> (or <term>one-to-one</term>) if each <m>\v{b}\in \R^m</m> is the image of at most one <m>\v{x}\in \R^n</m>. 
      </p>

      <p>
        That is, a mapping <m>T</m> is injective if <m>T(\v{x}_1) = T(\v{x}_2)</m> implies <m>\v{x}_1 = \v{x}_2</m>. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Notice how parallel each of these definitions is. 
    Moreover, these definitions have everything to do with the existence and uniqueness of pre-images: 
    <ul marker="">
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Existence: </em> Does each <m>\v{b}\in \R^m</m> have a pre-image? 
          If <m>T</m> is surjective, then Yes. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Uniqueness: </em> Is each solution to <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{b}</m> unique? 
          If <m>T</m> is injective, then Yes!
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    An immediate (and famous) result about injection is the following theorem: 
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-Injection-TrivialKernel">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T: \R^n \to \R^n</m> be a linear transformation. 
        Then <m>T</m> is injective if and only if <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <proof>
    <p>
      This is a biconditional statement. 
      Proving this statement comes in to parts: 
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Forward direction (<m>\Rightarrow</m>):</em> 
      Assume that <m>T</m> is injective. 
      We want to show that the equation <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Because <m>T</m> is a linear transformation, we know that it maps the zero vector to the zero vector, meaning <m>T(\v{0}) = \v{0}</m>. 
      Suppose there is some vector <m>\v{x}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> such that <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{0}</m>. 
      Then we have:
      <md>T(\v{x}) = T(\v{0})</md>
      Since we assumed <m>T</m> is injective, the outputs being equal guarantees that the inputs must also be equal. 
      Therefore, <m>\v{x} = \v{0}</m>. 
      This shows that the trivial solution is the only solution.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Backward direction (<m>\Leftarrow</m>):</em> 
      Assume that <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution. 
      We want to show that <m>T</m> is injective. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose there are vectors <m>\v{u}</m> and <m>\v{v}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> such that <m>T(\v{u}) = T(\v{v})</m>. 
      Subtracting <m>T(\v{v})</m> from both sides, we have
      <md>
        T(\v{u}) - T(\v{v}) = \v{0}
      </md>
      By the linearity properties, this implies that
      <md>
        T(\v{u} - \v{v}) = \v{0}
      </md>
      By our initial assumption, the only vector that maps to the zero vector is the zero vector itself.
      This forces the input to be zero.
      That is, 
      <md>
        \v{u} - \v{v} = \v{0}
      </md>
      This shows that <m>\v{u} = \v{v}</m>, and hence <m>T</m> is injective.
    </p>

    <p>
      What we have established that these two claims are either both true or both false (we assume one of them is true, and show the other one is also true). 
      Another way of calling biconditional statements are <em>equivalence</em> statement. 
    </p>
  </proof>
  
  <p>
    Last but not least, let's make a connection between these two types of the special transformations and what we have learned in the past through the following two statements!
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-Surjection-SpanCodomain">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> be a linear transformation with standard matrix <m>A</m>. 
        Then <m>T</m> is surjective if and only if the columns of <m>A</m> span the codomain, <m>\R^m</m>. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <proof>
    <p>
      Observe that the theorem is a biconditional statement. 
      But instead of proving both directions, let's do a slick trick! 
    </p>

    <p>
      Notation clarification! 
      The symbol <m>\implies</m> means implication!
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's consider the forward direction. 
      The chain of implication looks like this: 
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp T \text{ is surjective} </mrow>
        <mrow> \implies \qquad \amp \forall \v{b}\in \R^m, T(\v{x}) = \v{b} \text{ has at least one solution} </mrow>
        <mrow> \implies \qquad \amp \forall \v{b}\in \R^m, A\v{x} = \v{b} \text{ is consistent} </mrow>
        <mrow> \implies \qquad \amp \text{The columns of } A \text{ span } \R^m </mrow>
      </md>
      Okay. 
      And this is supposed to be impressive how? 
    </p>

    <p>
      Observe that the statements here are all equivalent! 
      That is, to prove the other direction, we can just reverse all the implication arrows and the argument stays true! 
      So the proof of this theorem is to change all the implication arrow to a biconditional arrow! 
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp T \text{ is surjective} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp \forall \v{b}\in \R^m, T(\v{x}) = \v{b} \text{ has at least one solution} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp \forall \v{b}\in \R^m, A\v{x} = \v{b} \text{ is consistent} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp \text{The columns of } A \text{ span } \R^m </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </proof>
  
  <theorem xml:id="thm-Injection-LinearIndependence">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T: \R^n \to \R^m</m> be a linear transformation with standard matrix <m>A</m>. 
        Then <m>T</m> is injective if and only if the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  
  <proof>
    <p>
      We can prove this theorem using the same slick trick! 
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp T \text{ is injective} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp T(\v{x}) = \v{0} \text{ has has only the trivial solution} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp A\v{x} = \v{0} \text{ has only the trivial solution} </mrow>
        <mrow> \iff \qquad \amp \text{The columns of } A \text{ are linearly independent }</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </proof>

  <example>
    <p>
      Let <m>T: \R^2 \to \R^3</m> defined by 
      <md>
        T\lp \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix} 3x_1 + x_2 \\ 5x_1 + 7x_2 \\ x_1 + 3x_2 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Is <m>T</m> a linear transformation? 
      Is it injective? 
      Is it surjective? 
    </p>

    <p>
      First, we determine if <m>T</m> is a linear transformation. 
      We can "factor out" the variables to rewrite the transformation as a matrix-vector product:
      <md>
        T(\v{x}) = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Let <m>A</m> be this <m>3 \times 2</m> matrix. 
      Because <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>, it is a matrix transformation. 
      Every matrix transformation is a linear transformation, so yes, <m>T</m> is a linear transformation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next, we check if <m>T</m> is injective. 
      By our previous theorem, <m>T</m> is injective if and only if the homogeneous equation <m>T(\v{x}) = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution. 
      To determine this, we find the reduced row echelon form of the standard matrix <m>A</m>:
      <md>
        \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 7 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp -8 \\ 0 \amp -8 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
      </md>
      Because there is a pivot in every column, there are no free variables. 
      The equation <m>A\v{x} = \v{0}</m> has only the trivial solution, <m>\v{x} = \v{0}</m>. 
      Therefore, <m>T</m> is injective.
    </p>

    <p>
      Finally, we determine if <m>T</m> is surjective. 
      The transformation <m>T</m> is surjective if and only if its columns span the codomain, <m>\R^3</m>. 
      This occurs if and only if there is a pivot position in every row of <m>A</m>. 
      Looking at the reduced row echelon form of <m>A</m>, the third row does not contain a pivot. 
      Consequently, the columns of <m>A</m> do not span <m>\R^3</m>, meaning there are vectors in the codomain that cannot be reached. 
      Thus, <m>T</m> is not surjective. 
    </p>
  </example>

</section>